Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis

Marks: 60

Context

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

# Write the code here
# Create a copy of the dataframe to process and modify the data
clean_df = df.copy()

# Drop columns from the dataframe that is not useful to analyze
cols_to_drop = ["order_id", "customer_id"]
clean_df.drop(cols_to_drop, axis=1, inplace=True)

# Convert the columns with datatype of object to category
cols_to_convert = ["restaurant_name", "cuisine_type", "day_of_the_week", "rating"]
clean_df[cols_to_convert] = clean_df[cols_to_convert].astype("category")

# Add a new column total_time = food_preparation_time + delivery_time
clean_df["total_time"] = clean_df["food_preparation_time"] + clean_df["delivery_time"]

# Create a copy of the clone dataframe with only rated restaurants
rated_df = clean_df.copy()
rated_df = rated_df[rated_df["rating"] != "Not given"]
rated_df["rating"] = rated_df["rating"].cat.remove_unused_categories().astype(int)

# Helper functions for plotting common layouts between multiple variables
def basic_num_cat_plots(data, x, y, title):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=3, sharey=True, figsize=(30, 15))

    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=x, y=y, ax= axes[0])
    sns.violinplot(data=data, x=x, y=y, ax= axes[1])
    sns.stripplot(data=data, x=x, y=y, size=3, ax=axes[2], jitter=True)

    fig.suptitle(title)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def hist_num_cat_plot(data, x, y, nrows, ncols, title):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows, ncols=ncols, sharey=True, figsize=(20, 8))
    axes = axes.ravel()
    for i, val in enumerate(data[y].unique()):
        sns.histplot(data=data[data[y] == val], x=x, kde=True, ax=axes[i])
        axes[i].set(title=f"{val} vs {x}", xlabel=x)
    fig.suptitle(title)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
In[30]:
# Visualize the relationship between rating and the total time it takes to reach the customer
basic_num_cat_plots(data=clean_df, x="rating", y="total_time", title="Total Time vs Rating Distribution Plots")
hist_num_cat_plot(data=clean_df, x="total_time", y="rating", nrows=2, ncols=2, title="Frequency Distribution of Total Time and Rating")

Observation

There seems to be no correlation between the total time it takes an order to reach a customer and the customer's rating of the order. This seems reasonable since most customers typically would not judge their order based on how long it takes for the food to arrive unless the time it takes is unacceptably long. In our dataset the maximum total time is 68 minutes, which is reasonable. Therefore this relation is not surprising. It should also be noted that each frequency plot follows a normal distribution.

In[31]:

Observation

The above plots show that the number of orders on weekends is much greater than that on weekdays. However, the minimum, average, and maximum total time on the weekends for orders to arrive to the customer are less than that on the weekdays. This is not surprising as there is typically more traffic on weekdays compared to weekends due to working hours. Furthermore, there is typically a tendency for customers to order less on weekdays as a means to save on unnecessary costs. Furthermore, it should be noted that the total time is takes for an order to be delivered on weekdays and weekends seem to follow a normal distribution.

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]

In[43]:
# Write the code here
# Create a copy of the dataframe to remove rows with no rating and convert the ratings to integers
clone = df.copy()
clone = clone[clone["rating"] != "Not given"]
clone["rating"] = clone["rating"].astype('int')

# Create GroupBy object based on restuarants
restaurant_group = clone.groupby(["restaurant_name"])
restaurant_ratings = restaurant_group["rating"]

# Select the eligible restaurants with > 50 ratings and an average rating of > 4.
eligible_restaurants = ((restaurant_ratings.count() > 50) & (restaurant_ratings.mean() > 4)).sort_values(ascending=False)

# Select only the rows of eligible restaurants that are True and drop all others
eligible_restaurants[eligible_restaurants == True]

Conclusion and Recommendations

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]

Conclusions:

After analyzing the data from FoodHub, there are a few key observations that stood out:

  • The app is most often used during the weekends with nearly 2.5x more orders compared to weekdays. Despite the increase in the app's usage, the company is not only able to keep up with the demand but also has a shorted total wait time for the customer to receive their order. Further investigation as to why this is the case may be warranted, however, my opinion on the matter is that people tend to prepare food at home or buy food near their work during the weekdays. The increased amount of time for orders to be received during weekdays may be due to increased traffic during working hours, or that there are less delivery people active during those times as they have other occupations during the week and use the app as a part-time job. Nevertheless, the app seems to be performing well given the demand on both weekdays and weekends.
  • The app is lossing out on acquiring useful rating data from its orders. Nearly 40% of all orders are not rated which reduced the company's capability of ranking and recommending restaurants and cuisine types to old and new users. Time and effort should be put into remedying this issue in order to allow the company to improve its systems.
  • Most orders tend to range between $10 to $20, with approximately 70% of orders being priced at less than $20. Therefore, promoting high cost dishes may not in general be fruitful to users on FoodHub. In particular, cuisines like French food which have a high average cost may not be the most appropriate for the app.
  • The American, Japanese, Italian, and Chinese cuisines are the most popular on the app. These appear to be staples of the types of food users enjoy and promoting them may deem fruitful.
  • The Vietnamese cuisine is the worst performing cuisine on the app, with the lowest rating and the lowest number of orders. Simiarly, the Korean cuisine does not seem to be performing well on the app. This may be due to it being a more exotic type of cuisine and less popular compared to Japanese, Chinese, and Thai food. If it costs the company money to keep restaurants, it may be best to remove this cuisines entirely.
  • There are some cuisines, such as Spanish, Mexican, and Thai that are well rated considering their lower order numbers. Compared to the other popular cuisines, these seem secondary, however increased exposure to users may cause them to try restaurants serving these cuisines and increase their interest in more niche foods in the future.
  • There seems to be no correlation between the data from users on the app, which indicates that there is a sufficiently diverse set of users and restaurants on the app that no overwhelming pattern has emerged to be exploited.

Recommendations:

  • The company should investigate a few options to incentivize users to rate their orders. Perhaps promotional offers or discount codes for a certain number of rated orders while using the app.
  • Since the usage of the app is nearly 2.5x less on weekdays compared to weekends, perhaps the comapny can look into adding promotional or discount codes during weekdays to incentive users to use the app more. This needs to be done careful as to not loss out on revenue from the excessive usage of discounts.
  • The company should look into removing or reducing the Vietnamese, Korean, and French cuisine restaurants on the app if it costs them to money to maintain them on the app.
  • The company should look into increasing expsoure for cuisines that have low order counts but high ratings in order to have users explore niche foods and potentially use the app more often for their exploration and in turn improving overall app usage and company revenue.
  • The company may find it useful in developing a recommendation system between customers with similar food interests in order to improve user experience and perhaps also restaurant ratings (which can lead to more user interactions).
